  "title": "Network covalent solid BP",
  "content": {
    "prompt": "<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents 2 allotropes of solid phosphorus. The diagram on the left is labeled “Allotrope 1,” and contains discrete tetrahedral P 4 molecules that are not connected to one another. The diagram on the right is labeled “Allotrope 2,” and contains numerous P atoms interconnected by single bonds to form a 3 dimensional network.\" height=\"286\" src=\"/images/566dd450e91a3fc8304e484370decda8.png\" width=\"500\"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The diagrams above represent two allotropes of solid phosphorus. Which of the following correctly identifies the allotrope with the higher melting point and explains why?</p>\n",
    "answer": "i2",
    "choices": [
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Allotrope <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>I</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, because it has <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P 4\"><math alttext=\"P 4\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mtext>P</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> molecules with covalent bonds that are stronger than dispersion forces between individual <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>P</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> atoms in allotrope <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>II</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>",
        "value": "i1"
      },
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Allotrope <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>II</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, because it has covalent bonds between the phosphorous atoms that are stronger than the dispersion forces between the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P 4\"><math alttext=\"P 4\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mtext>P</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> molecules in allotrope <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>I</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>",
        "value": "i2"
      },
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Allotrope <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>II</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, because it has metallic bonding that is stronger than the covalent bonding found in the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P 4\"><math alttext=\"P 4\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mtext>P</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> molecules in allotrope <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>I</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>",
        "value": "i3"
      },
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Both allotropes have the same melting point because they both contain phosphorous atoms.</p>",
        "value": "i4"
      }
    ]
  },
